New object/array/function ref each parent render. Passed as prop = new ref = child sees "changed" prop = re-render. React default shallow-compare props only if wrapped.

Common causes:
- Inline prop: `<Child data={{...}} />` or `onClick={() => ...}` — new ref every render
- Child not memoized — re-renders anyway when parent renders, even if props same
- Context value new object each render

Fix:

```jsx
// 1. Memoize child
const Child = React.memo(function Child(props) { ... });

// 2. Stable prop refs in parent
const data = useMemo(() => ({ id, name }), [id, name]);
const handleClick = useCallback(() => doThing(id), [id]);

<Child data={data} onClick={handleClick} />
```

Key point: `React.memo` alone not enough if props get new ref each render. Need both. Without `React.memo`, child ALWAYS re-render when parent render — that normal React behavior, memoize child to stop it.

Check which case you hit: parent re-render + no memo = expected. Add `React.memo` first.

Debounce wait for user stop typing before fire search. Point:

- **Less requests.** Type "laptop" = 6 keystrokes. No debounce = 6 API calls. Debounce = 1 call after typing stop. Save server load + bandwidth.
- **Less wasted work.** Intermediate queries ("l", "la", "lap") useless. User no care result for them.
- **Avoid race.** Fast requests can return out of order — stale response overwrite fresh one. Fewer calls = fewer races.
- **Smoother UI.** No flicker from result list changing every keystroke.
- **Save money.** Fewer calls to paid search/API.

Typical wait: 250–400ms. 

```js
const [q, setQ] = useState("");
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setTimeout(() => runSearch(q), 300);
  return () => clearTimeout(id); // cancel if key press before 300ms
}, [q]);
```

Related: **throttle** different — fire at fixed rate during typing, not after stop. Search input want debounce.
